rbyshire, from Old English <i>brād</i> ‘broad’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘thicket’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brayshaw","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Bradshaw  , reflecting the local Yorkshire pronunciation."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecilia Bradshaw was born in 1210, in Standish, Lancashire, England, her father, Roger De Bradshaw, was 25 and her mother, Lady Alica Osbaldston, was 20. She married Ralph Standish in 1247, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1234, in her hometown."},"et":{"1210–Aft. 1234":"1210–pärast 1234","1210–1234":"1210–1234","1208–1246":"1208–1246","1208–1288":"1208–1288","1234–1290":"1234–1290","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1232–1240":"1232–1240","1185–1235":"1185–1235","1190–1210":"1190–1210","Aft. 1234":"pärast 1234","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1234":"1234","1288":"1288","1210":"1210","1232":"1232","1208":"1208","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1210–Aft. 1234":"1210–1234 jälkeen","1210–1234":"1210–1234","1208–1246":"1208–1246","1208–1288":"1208–1288","1234–1290":"1234–1290","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1232–1240":"1232–1240","1185–1235":"1185–1235","1190–1210":"1190–1210","Aft. 1234":"1234 jälkeen","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1234":"1234","1288":"1288","1210":"1210","1232":"1232","1208":"1208","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1210–Aft. 1234":"1210–après 1234","1210–1234":"1210–1234","1208–1246":"1208–1246","1208–1288":"1208–1288","1234–1290":"1234–1290","1230–1280":"1230–1280","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1232–1240":"1232–1240","1185–1235":"1185–1235","1190–1210":"1190–1210","Aft. 1234":"après 1234","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","1185"